If we use our own abilities and biases as a starting point, we end up with services designed for people of a specific gender, age, language ability, tech literacy, and physical ability.

## There’s no such thing as a "normal user". 

The interactions we design with technology depend heavily on what we can see, hear, say, and touch. 

Assuming all those senses and abilities are fully enabled all the time creates the potential to ignore many people who may have impairments with one or more of their senses.

## Why you should care as a designer

We want our services and what we design to reflect the diversity of our users.

Designing for inclusivity not only opens up Department for Education (DfE) services to more people with a wider range of abilities. It also reflects how people really are. 

Every decision we make can raise or lower barriers to participation in society. It’s our collective responsibility to lower these barriers though inclusive products and services.


## Recognise exclusion in design

Exclusion happens when we solve problems using our own biases.

There are different ways someone can be exluded from using a service through disability and it is dependent on the context the user is using your service. 

There are three types of exclusion designers must consider when desinging services, components and features.

### Temporary 

Short term injury or context affects how users interact with your service. For example, having a broken arm may make it more difficult to use a phone, computer or mouse and keyboard.

### Situational

The situation a user finds themself in might mean they cannot use your service at that time. For example, being in a loud environment might make it difficult to hear or speak to someone on the phone if they need help using a service.

### Permanent

Many people have a permanent disability and so designing for these users by default means your service will work for more people. For example, ensuring a service works with screen readers will work for a wide range of people.

